[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] In combinatorial mathematics, the **Bell polynomials**, named in honor of Eric Temple Bell, are used in the study of set partitions.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] They are related to Stirling and Bell numbers.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] They also occur in many applications, such as in Faà di Bruno's formula and an explicit formula for Lagrange inversion.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] is called the *n*th *complete exponential Bell polynomial*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] where we have used the multinomial coefficient.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] In general, Bell polynomial refers to the exponential Bell polynomial, unless otherwise explicitly stated.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] The exponential Bell polynomial encodes the information related to the ways a set can be partitioned.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Here, the subscripts of *B*3,2 tell us that we are considering the partitioning of a set with 3 elements into 2 blocks.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] The subscript of each *x*i indicates the presence of a block with *i* elements (or block of size *i*) in a given partition.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] So here, *x*2 indicates the presence of a block with two elements.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Similarly, *x*1 indicates the presence of a block with a single element.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] The exponent of *x*ij indicates that there are *j* such blocks of size *i* in a single partition.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Here, the fact that both *x*1 and *x*2 have exponent 1 indicates that there is only one such block in a given partition.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] The coefficient of the monomial indicates how many such partitions there are.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Here, there are 3 partitions of a set with 3 elements into 2 blocks, where in each partition the elements are divided into two blocks of sizes 1 and 2.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Since any set can be divided into a single block in only one way, the above interpretation would mean that *B**n*,1 = *x**n*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Similarly, since there is only one way that a set with *n* elements be divided into *n* singletons, *B**n*,*n* = *x*1*n*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] This tells us that if a set with 6 elements is divided into 2 blocks, then we can have 6 partitions with blocks of size 1 and 5, 15 partitions with blocks of size 4 and 2, and 10 partitions with 2 blocks of size 3.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] The sum of the subscripts in a monomial is equal to the total number of elements.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Thus, the number of monomials that appear in the partial Bell polynomial is equal to the number of ways the integer *n* can be expressed as a summation of *k* positive integers.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] This is the same as the integer partition of *n* into *k* parts.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] For instance, in the above examples, the integer 3 can be partitioned into two parts as 2+1 only.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Thus, there is only one monomial in *B*3,2.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] However, the integer 6 can be partitioned into two parts as 5+1, 4+2, and 3+3.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Thus, there are three monomials in *B*6,2.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Indeed, the subscripts of the variables in a monomial are the same as those given by the integer partition, indicating the sizes of the different blocks.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] The total number of monomials appearing in a complete Bell polynomial *Bn* is thus equal to the total number of integer partitions of *n*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Also the degree of each monomial, which is the sum of the exponents of each variable in the monomial, is equal to the number of blocks the set is divided into.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Thus, given a complete Bell polynomial *Bn*, we can separate the partial Bell polynomial *Bn,k* by collecting all those monomials with degree *k*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] Also, the summation of all the coefficients of the complete Bell polynomial *Bn* will give us the total number of ways a set with *n* elements can be partitioned into non-overlapping subsets, which is the same as the Bell number.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] 10 ways to partition a set of 6 as 3 + 3.
[src:generating-functions-deep/bell-polynomials] 15 ways to partition a set of 6 as 2 + 2 + 2.
