[src:generating-functions-deep/dirichlet-series] In mathematics, a **Dirichlet series** is any series of the form $\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }{\frac {a_{n}}{n^{s}}},$ where *s* is complex, and $a_{n}$ is a complex sequence.
[src:generating-functions-deep/dirichlet-series] It is a special case of general Dirichlet series.
[src:generating-functions-deep/dirichlet-series] Dirichlet series play a variety of important roles in analytic number theory.
[src:generating-functions-deep/dirichlet-series] The most usually seen definition of the Riemann zeta function is a Dirichlet series, as are the Dirichlet *L*-functions.
[src:generating-functions-deep/dirichlet-series] where *D*(*u*, *s*) denotes the Dirichlet series of *u*(*n*).
[src:generating-functions-deep/dirichlet-series] It is conjectured that the Selberg class of series obeys the generalized Riemann hypothesis.
[src:generating-functions-deep/dirichlet-series] The series is named in honor of Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet.
[src:generating-functions-deep/dirichlet-series] Dirichlet series can be used as generating series for counting weighted sets of objects with respect to a weight which is combined multiplicatively when taking Cartesian products.
[src:generating-functions-deep/dirichlet-series] Suppose that *A* is a set with a function *w* : *A* → **N** assigning a weight to each of the elements of *A*, and suppose additionally that the fibre over any natural number under that weight is a finite set.
[src:generating-functions-deep/dirichlet-series] (We call such an arrangement (*A*, *w*) a weighted set.) Suppose additionally that *an* is the number of elements of *A* with weight *n*.
