[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] In mathematics, a **formal series** is an infinite sum that is considered independently from any notion of convergence, and can be manipulated with the usual algebraic operations on series (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, partial sums, etc.).
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] Hence, formal power series can be viewed as a generalization of polynomials where the number of terms is allowed to be infinite, and differ from usual power series by the absence of convergence requirements, which implies that a formal power series may not represent a function of its variables.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] Formal power series are in one to one correspondence with their sequences of coefficients, but the two concepts must not be confused, since the operations that can be applied are different.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] Formal powers series in several indeterminates are defined similarly by replacing the powers of a single indeterminate by monomials in several indeterminates.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] Formal power series are widely used in combinatorics for representing sequences of integers as generating functions.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] In this context, a recurrence relation between the elements of a sequence may often be interpreted as a differential equation that the generating function satisfies.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] This allows using methods of complex analysis for combinatorial problems (see analytic combinatorics).
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] A formal power series can be loosely thought of as an object that is like a polynomial, but with infinitely many terms.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] Alternatively, for those familiar with power series (or Taylor series), one may think of a formal power series as a power series in which we ignore questions of convergence by not assuming that the variable *X* denotes any numerical value (not even an unknown value).
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] For example, consider the series $A=1-3X+5X^{2}-7X^{3}+9X^{4}-11X^{5}+\cdots .$ If we studied this as a power series, its properties would include, for example, that its radius of convergence is 1 by the Cauchy–Hadamard theorem.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] However, as a formal power series, we may ignore this completely; all that is relevant is the sequence of coefficients [1, −3, 5, −7, 9, −11, ...].
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] In other words, a formal power series is an object that just records a sequence of coefficients.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] It is perfectly acceptable to consider a formal power series with the factorials [1, 1, 2, 6, 24, 120, 720, 5040, ... ] as coefficients, even though the corresponding power series diverges for any nonzero value of *X*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] Algebra on formal power series is carried out by simply pretending that the series are polynomials.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] Notice that each coefficient in the product *AB* only depends on a *finite* number of coefficients of *A* and *B*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] For this reason, one may multiply formal power series without worrying about the usual questions of absolute, conditional and uniform convergence which arise in dealing with power series in the setting of analysis.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] Once we have defined multiplication for formal power series, we can define multiplicative inverses as follows.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] The multiplicative inverse of a formal power series *A* is a formal power series *C* such that *AC* = 1, provided that such a formal power series exists.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] It turns out that if *A* has a multiplicative inverse, it is unique, and we denote it by *A*−1.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] Now we can define division of formal power series by defining *B*/*A* to be the product *BA*−1, provided that the inverse of *A* exists.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] An important operation on formal power series is coefficient extraction.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] In its most basic form, the coefficient extraction operator $[X^{n}]$ applied to a formal power series A in one variable extracts the coefficient of the n th power of the variable, so that $[X^{2}]A=5$ and $[X^{5}]A=-11$ .
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] Similarly, many other operations that are carried out on polynomials can be extended to the formal power series setting, as explained below.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] If one considers the set of all formal power series in *X* with coefficients in a commutative ring *R*, the elements of this set collectively constitute another ring which is written $R[[X]],$ and called the **ring of formal power series** in the variable *X* over *R*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] One can characterize $R[[X]]$ abstractly as the completion of the polynomial ring $R[X]$ equipped with a particular metric.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] This automatically gives $R[[X]]$ the structure of a topological ring (and even of a complete metric space).
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] But the general construction of a completion of a metric space is more involved than what is needed here, and would make formal power series seem more complicated than they are.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] It is possible to describe $R[[X]]$ more explicitly, and define the ring structure and topological structure separately, as follows.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] As a set, $R[[X]]$ can be constructed as the set $R^{\mathbb {N} }$ of all infinite sequences of elements of R , indexed by the natural numbers (taken to include 0).
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] This type of product is called the Cauchy product of the two sequences of coefficients, and is a sort of discrete convolution.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] With these operations, $R^{\mathbb {N} }$ becomes a commutative ring with zero element $(0,0,0,\ldots )$ and multiplicative identity $(1,0,0,\ldots )$ .
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] The product is in fact the same one used to define the product of polynomials in one indeterminate, which suggests using a similar notation.
[src:generating-functions-deep/formal-power-series] these are precisely the polynomials in X .
