[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] In mathematics, a **generating function** is a representation of an infinite sequence of numbers as the coefficients of a formal power series.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Generating functions are often expressed in closed form (rather than as a series), by some expression involving operations on the formal series.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] There are various types of generating functions, including **ordinary generating functions**, **exponential generating functions**, *Lambert series*, *Bell series*, and *Dirichlet series*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Every sequence in principle has a generating function of each type (except that Lambert and Dirichlet series require indices to start at 1 rather than 0), but the ease with which they can be handled may differ considerably.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] The particular generating function, if any, that is most useful in a given context will depend upon the nature of the sequence and the details of the problem being addressed.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Generating functions are sometimes called **generating series**, in that a series of terms can be said to be the generator of its sequence of term coefficients.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Generating functions were first introduced by Abraham de Moivre in 1730, in order to solve the general linear recurrence problem.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Unlike an ordinary series, the *formal* power series is not required to converge: in fact, the generating function is not actually regarded as a function, and the "variable" remains an indeterminate.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] One can generalize to formal power series in more than one indeterminate, to encode information about infinite multi-dimensional arrays of numbers.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Thus generating functions are not functions in the formal sense of a mapping from a domain to a codomain.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] These expressions in terms of the indeterminate x may involve arithmetic operations, differentiation with respect to x and composition with (i.e., substitution into) other generating functions; since these operations are also defined for functions, the result looks like a function of x.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Indeed, the closed form expression can often be interpreted as a function that can be evaluated at (sufficiently small) concrete values of x, and which has the formal series as its series expansion; this explains the designation "generating functions".
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] However such interpretation is not required to be possible, because formal series are not required to give a convergent series when a nonzero numeric value is substituted for x.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Not all expressions that are meaningful as functions of x are meaningful as expressions designating formal series; for example, negative and fractional powers of x are examples of functions that do not have a corresponding formal power series.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] When the term *generating function* is used without qualification, it is usually taken to mean an ordinary generating function.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] The *ordinary generating function* of a sequence *a**n* is: $G(a_{n};x)=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }a_{n}x^{n}.$ If *a**n* is the probability mass function of a discrete random variable, then its ordinary generating function is called a probability-generating function.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Exponential generating functions are generally more convenient than ordinary generating functions for combinatorial enumeration problems that involve labelled objects.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Another benefit of exponential generating functions is that they are useful in transferring linear recurrence relations to the realm of differential equations.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] For example, take the Fibonacci sequence {*fn*} that satisfies the linear recurrence relation *f**n*+2 = *f**n*+1 + *f**n*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] and its derivatives can readily be shown to satisfy the differential equation EF″(*x*) = EF′(*x*) + EF(*x*) as a direct analogue with the recurrence relation above.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] In this view, the factorial term *n*! is merely a counter-term to normalise the derivative operator acting on *x**n*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] The *Lambert series* of a sequence *a**n* is $\operatorname {LG} (a_{n};x)=\sum _{n=1}^{\infty }a_{n}{\frac {x^{n}}{1-x^{n}}}.$ Note that in a Lambert series the index n starts at 1, not at 0, as the first term would otherwise be undefined.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Formal Dirichlet series are often classified as generating functions, although they are not strictly formal power series.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] If *a**n* is a Dirichlet character then its Dirichlet series generating function is called a Dirichlet L-series.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] We also have a relation between the pair of coefficients in the Lambert series expansions above and their DGFs.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Namely, we can prove that: $[x^{n}]\operatorname {LG} (a_{n};x)=b_{n}$ if and only if $\operatorname {DG} (a_{n};s)\zeta (s)=\operatorname {DG} (b_{n};s),$ where *ζ*(*s*) is the Riemann zeta function.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] The idea of generating functions can be extended to sequences of other objects.
[src:generating-functions-deep/generating-function-p01] Thus, for example, polynomial sequences of binomial type are generated by: $e^{xf(t)}=\sum _{n=0}^{\infty }{\frac {p_{n}(x)}{n!}}t^{n}$ where *p**n*(*x*) is a sequence of polynomials and *f*(*t*) is a function of a certain form.
