[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] In combinatorics, the **symbolic method** is a technique for counting combinatorial objects.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] It uses the internal structure of the objects to derive formulas for their generating functions.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] During two centuries, generating functions were popping up via the corresponding recurrences on their coefficients (as can be seen in the seminal works of Bernoulli, Euler, Arthur Cayley, Schröder, Ramanujan, Riordan, Knuth, Comtet, etc.).
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] Note that this symbolic method in enumeration is unrelated to "Blissard's symbolic method", which is just another old name for umbral calculus.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] The symbolic method in combinatorics constitutes the first step of many analyses of combinatorial structures, which can then lead to fast computation schemes, to asymptotic properties and limit laws, to random generation, all of them being suitable to automatization via computer algebra.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] We will first explain how to solve this problem in the labelled and the unlabelled case and use the solution to motivate the creation of classes of combinatorial structures.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] The Pólya enumeration theorem solves this problem in the unlabelled case.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] We are able to enumerate filled slot configurations using either Pólya enumeration theorem in the unlabelled case or the labelled enumeration theorem in the labelled case.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] We now ask about the generating function of configurations obtained when there is more than one set of slots, with a permutation group acting on each.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] Clearly the orbits do not intersect and we may add the respective generating functions.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] Suppose, for example, that we want to enumerate unlabelled sequences of length two or three of some objects contained in a set *X*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] There are two sets of slots, the first one containing two slots, and the second one, three slots.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] The group acting on the first set is the full symmetric group $S_{2}$ , which in symbolic combinatorics is traditionally denoted $E_{2}$ .
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] The group acting on the second set is, analogously, $S_{3}=E_{3}$ .
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] where the term $X^{n}/G$ is used to denote the set of orbits under *G* and $X^{n}=X\times \cdots \times X$ , which denotes in the obvious way the process of distributing the objects from *X* with repetition into the *n* slots.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] Similarly, consider the labelled problem of creating cycles of arbitrary length from a set of labelled objects *X*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] Clearly we can assign meaning to any such power series of quotients (orbits) with respect to permutation groups, where we restrict the groups of degree *n* to the conjugacy classes $\operatorname {Cl} (S_{n})$ of the symmetric group $S_{n}$ , which form a unique factorization domain.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] (The orbits with respect to two groups from the same conjugacy class are isomorphic.) This motivates the following definition.
