[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] The elementary constructions mentioned above allow us to define the notion of *specification*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] This specification allows us to use a set of recursive equations, with multiple combinatorial classes.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] A class of combinatorial structures is said to be *constructible* or *specifiable* when it admits a specification.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] For example, the set of trees whose leaves' depth is even (respectively, odd) can be defined using the specification with two classes ${\mathcal {A}}_{\text{even}}$ and ${\mathcal {A}}_{\text{odd}}$ .
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] An object is *weakly labelled* if each of its atoms has a nonnegative integer label, and each of these labels is distinct.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] An object is (*strongly* or *well*) *labelled*, if furthermore, these labels comprise the consecutive integers $[1\ldots n]$ .
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] *Note: some combinatorial classes are best specified as labelled structures or unlabelled structures, but some readily admit both specifications.* A good example of labelled structures is the class of labelled graphs.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] With labelled structures, an exponential generating function (EGF) is used.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] For labelled structures, we must use a different definition for product than for unlabelled structures.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] In fact, if we simply used the cartesian product, the resulting structures would not even be well labelled.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] For a pair $\beta \in {\mathcal {B}}$ and $\gamma \in {\mathcal {C}}$ , we wish to combine the two structures into a single structure.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] In order for the result to be well labelled, this requires some relabelling of the atoms in $\beta$ and $\gamma$ .
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] We will restrict our attention to relabellings that are consistent with the order of the original labels.
[src:generating-functions-deep/symbolic-method-combinatorics] Note that there are still multiple ways to do the relabelling; thus, each pair of members determines not a single member in the product, but a set of new members.
