[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] The term **umbral calculus** has two related but distinct meanings.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] In mathematics, before the 1970s, umbral calculus referred to the surprising similarity between seemingly unrelated polynomial equations and certain shadowy techniques used to prove them.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] These techniques were introduced in 1861 by John Blissard and are sometimes called **Blissard's symbolic method**.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] They are often attributed to Édouard Lucas (or James Joseph Sylvester), who used the technique extensively.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] The use of shadowy techniques was put on a solid mathematical footing starting in the 1970s, and the resulting mathematical theory is also referred to as "umbral calculus".
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] In the 1930s and 1940s, Eric Temple Bell attempted to set the umbral calculus on a rigorous footing, however his attempt in making this kind of argument logically rigorous was unsuccessful.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] The combinatorialist John Riordan in his book *Combinatorial Identities* published in the 1960s, used techniques of this sort extensively.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] In the 1970s, Gian-Carlo Rota, with Steven Roman and others, developed the umbral calculus by means of linear functions on spaces of polynomials.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] Currently, *umbral calculus* refers to the study of Sheffer sequences, including polynomial sequences of binomial type and Appell sequences, but may encompass systematic correspondence techniques of the calculus of finite differences.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] The method is a notational procedure used for deriving identities involving indexed sequences of numbers by *pretending that the indices are exponents*.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] Construed literally, it is absurd, and yet it is successful: identities derived via the umbral calculus can also be properly derived by more complicated methods that can be taken literally without logical difficulty.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] An example involves the Bernoulli polynomials.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] These similarities allow one to construct *umbral* proofs, which on the surface cannot be correct, but seem to work anyway.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] In the above, the variable *b* is an "umbra" (Latin for *shadow*).
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] In differential calculus, the Taylor series of a function is an infinite sum of terms that are expressed in terms of the function's derivatives at a single point.
[src:generating-functions-deep/umbral-calculus] Similar relationships were also observed in the theory of finite differences.
